Adjust rack to top position and preheat #oven{} to 450 degrees. Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Once water is boiling, add @penne pasta{12%ounce} to pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}. Drain.

While pasta cooks, heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%teaspoon} in a large pan over medium-high heat.

Add @ground pork{20%ounce} and cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Season with @Tuscan Heat Spice{1%tablespoon}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Stir to combine.

Stir @marinara cup{28%ounce} and @milk{1} into pan with pork. Cook, stirring occasionally, until sauce begins to bubble, then remove from heat.

Stir in @spinach{5%ounce} and as many @chili flakes{1%teaspoon} as you like. Cover pan until spinach wilts. Stir in half the @mozzarella cheese{1%cup}. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Transfer drained penne to a #9-by-13-inch baking dish{}.

Carefully pour sauce over pasta and stir until sauce is evenly distributed.

Evenly top pasta mixture in baking dish with @panko breadcrumbs{1/2%cup}, remaining mozzarella, and a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon}.

Bake until panko is browned and crispy, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Divide casserole between plates or serve family style directly from baking dish.

> Ground Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.